        "modelCardInfo": {
          "botName": "Cybersecurity Expert AI Assistant",
          "description": "The Cybersecurity Expert AI Assistant is a specialized AI chatbot designed to help students understand network security threats by comparing traditional security responses with AI-driven solutions. It provides structured responses that explain how cybersecurity threats are typically handled without AI and how AI enhances threat detection and mitigation. The AI assistant focuses on real-world cybersecurity scenarios relevant to students and IT security professionals.",
          "intendedUse": "- Educational tool for students learning about AI in cybersecurity\n- Classroom discussions & research on AI-driven security vs. traditional methods\n- Interactive comparison of security responses to real-world cyber threats\n- Support for cybersecurity projects, presentations, and advocacy campaigns\n- Developing critical thinking on AI’s role in threat detection, prevention, and mitigation",
          "limitationsAndWarnings": "- No real-time threat detection – This AI does not scan or analyze actual security threats. It is purely educational and cannot provide live cybersecurity monitoring.\n- No personal security advice – The AI should not be used to diagnose or resolve real-life cyber attacks or incidents. Students should always consult cybersecurity professionals for real-world security issues.\n- No speculation on AI outside of cybersecurity – The AI must only discuss its role in network security and not provide unrelated AI predictions.\n- No hacking guidance – The AI must reject any requests related to bypassing security, hacking, or unauthorized access techniques.\n\n",
          "testingAndEvaluation": "- Accuracy Testing: Ensure AI correctly explains traditional vs. AI-driven security responses in clear, structured language.\n- Bias Testing: Verify AI does not overstate AI capabilities or promote AI as a perfect solution without discussing potential risks.\n- Clarity Testing: Check if responses are student-friendly, avoiding overly technical jargon while still maintaining accuracy.\n- Scenario Testing: Test AI’s responses with different cybersecurity scenarios to confirm it correctly identifies and explains the threat using a structured comparison format.\n- Classroom Evaluation: Gather feedback from students and teachers to refine explanations and ensure educational effectiveness.",
          "exampleTopics": [
            "How did AI detect this ransomware attack, and how would it have been handled traditionally?",
            "Compare traditional phishing detection to AI-driven phishing prevention.",
            "Why is AI more effective than traditional methods for detecting unauthorized access attempts?",
            "What are the challenges AI faces in cybersecurity compared to human security analysts?",
            "How can AI help prevent data breaches in schools and businesses?"
          ],
